  <validation>
    - Identify the PRNG algorithm used
    - Demonstrate prediction of at least one future value
    - Show correlation between outputs (sequential, time-based)
    - Exploit prediction for session hijacking or token forgery
    - Document the security impact of prediction
  </validation>

  <false_positives>
    - Cryptographically secure PRNGs (CSPRNG)
    - Values that include additional entropy (server-side secrets)
    - HMAC or hash-based token derivation with secret key
    - High entropy values that resist statistical analysis
  </false_positives>

  <detection_indicators>
    - High volume of session/token collection requests
    - Sequential probing of token space
    - Multiple authentication attempts with predicted values
    - Password reset requests at precise time intervals
  </detection_indicators>

  <pro_tips>
    - Math.random() in JavaScript is NEVER safe for security purposes
    - PHP's mt_rand() can be cracked with ~624 outputs
    - Time-based seeding reduces entropy to seconds in a day (~86400)
    - Look for patterns in UUIDs - v1 uses timestamp, v4 should be random
    - Some frameworks use weak PRNG by default - check documentation
    - Server restart may reset PRNG state to predictable seed
    - Token length doesn't equal security if PRNG is weak
    - Collect tokens from different users/sessions to analyze generator
  </pro_tips>

  <remember>A weak PRNG makes all cryptographic operations built on it worthless. Session tokens, password reset links, and CSRF tokens are only secure if generated with cryptographically secure randomness.</remember>
</vulnerability_guide>
